narrative elements in organizing the progressive course of the poetic text. This observation justifies the application of the advanced methodology of narratology to the systematic analysis of lyric poems. After a concise presentation of this transgeneric approach to poetry, the study sets out to demonstrate its practical fruitfulness in detailed analyses of a large number of English (and some American) poems from the early modern period to the present. The narratological approach proves particularly suited to focus on the hitherto widely neglected dimension of sequentiality, the dynamic progression of the poetic utterance and its eventful turns, which largely constitute the raison d'être of the poem. To facilitate comparisons, the examples chosen share one special thematic complex, the traumatic experience of severe loss: the death of a beloved person, the imminence of one’s own death, the death of a revered fellow-poet and the loss of a fundamental stabilizing order. The function of the poems can be described as facing the traumatic experience in the poetic medium and employing various coping strategies. The poems thus possess a therapeutic impetus.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aBereavement in literature. 0aEnglish poetryxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aLoss (Psychology) in literature. 0aLyric poetryxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aNarration (Rhetoric)xHistory. 4aEreignishaftigkeit. 4aGedichtanalyse. 4aTod. 4aTransgenerische Narratologie. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aPoetry analysis.  aeventfulness.  asequentiality.  atransgeneric narratology.1 aGoerke, Britta , econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoerke, Britta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHühn, Peter, econtribut